Q1: Eigenvalues of a symmetric matrix

  • Suppose that \(A\) is an \(n\times n\) matrix and that \(x\) is a vector in \(\mathbb{R}^n\). Is \(x^TAx\) a number, vector, or matrix?

Solution:

\(x^T\) is a \(1 \times n\) vector, \(A\) is a \(n \times n\) matrix, \(x\) is a \(n \times 1\) vector. So when they time together, the result \(x^TAx\) will be a number.

  • Suppose that \(Ax = \lambda x\) and \(A = A^T\) and \(x\) is not all zeros; that is, \(\lambda\) is an eigenvector of a symmetric matrix \(A\) with eigenvalue \(\lambda\). Show that \(x^TAx = \lambda x^Tx\). Explain why this means that \(\lambda\) must be a real number.

Solution:

Since \(A\) is real, \(\overline{A} = A\), \(\overline{A}\) here is the element-wise complex conjugate. \[A\overline{x} = \overline{\lambda}\overline{x}\] Then, we can transpose both side adn we will get \[\overline{x}^{T}A = \overline{\lambda}\overline{x}^{T}\] So, we can get \[\overline{\lambda}\overline{x}^{T}x = \overline{x}^{T}Ax = \overline{x}^{T}\lambda x=\lambda \overline{x}^{T}x\] Since \(x \neq 0\), \[\overline{x}^{T}x = \overline{x}_{1} \cdot x_{1} + \overline{x}_{2} \cdot x_{2} + \cdots + \overline{x}_{n} \cdot x_{n} > 0\] So, we can get \(\overline{\lambda} = \lambda\) from \(\overline{\lambda}\overline{x}^{T}x = \lambda \overline{x}^{T}x\), which means \(\lambda\) is real.

  • Form the matrices \(P\) and \(S\) in R and use the syntax eigen(A)$values to find their eigenvalues. (According to the result we proved, \(S\) should have real eigenvalues and \(P\) might or might not have real eigenvalues). \[P = \begin{pmatrix} -4&5&6\\1&0&9 \\9&1&2\end{pmatrix} \qquad S = \begin{pmatrix} -1&2&1\\2&7&-3\\1&-3&4\end{pmatrix} \]

Solution:

P <- matrix(c(-4, 1, 9, 5, 0, 1, 6, 9, 2), nrow = 3, ncol = 3)
P
##      [,1] [,2] [,3]
## [1,]   -4    5    6
## [2,]    1    0    9
## [3,]    9    1    2
S <- matrix(c(-1, 2, 1, 2, 7, -3, 1, -3, 4), nrow = 3, ncol = 3)
S
##      [,1] [,2] [,3]
## [1,]   -1    2    1
## [2,]    2    7   -3
## [3,]    1   -3    4
eigen(S)$values
## [1]  8.999999999999998  3.000000000000006 -1.999999999999996
eigen(P)$values
## [1]  9.988620673572962+0.00000000000000i -5.994310336786480+2.79607365674972i
## [3] -5.994310336786480-2.79607365674972i

Q2: Nearly R-O

Write some code to create and print out this matrix (its possible to do it in two lines, but any solution is fine as long as you dont separately type all 16 entries). Explain why it is nearly a R-O matrix, where R-O stands for something on our first-day slides. \[ A = \begin{pmatrix} 1&3&5&10\\ 10&30&50&100\\ -2&-6&-10&-20\\ 100&300&4&4 \end{pmatrix} \]

Solution:

x <- c(1, 10, -2, 100)
A <- matrix(c(x, 3*x, 5*x, 10*x), nrow = 4, ncol = 4)
A[4, 3:4] <- 4
A
##      [,1] [,2] [,3] [,4]
## [1,]    1    3    5   10
## [2,]   10   30   50  100
## [3,]   -2   -6  -10  -20
## [4,]  100  300    4    4

It is nearly a rank one matrix because after we change \(A_{43}\) to 500, \(A_{44}\) to 1000, each column of the matrix is the multiple of the first column.

Q3: Basic graph example

Write some code to plot the quadratic function \(y=x^2 - 5x + 2\). Make sure that the minimum is visible inside your figure.

Solution:

library(ggplot2)


sigmoid <- function(x) x**2-5*x+2
x<-seq(-10, 15, by=0.01)
y<-sigmoid(x)
df<-data.frame(x, y)

g <- ggplot(df, aes(x,y)) +
  geom_line(col='black') +
  geom_hline(yintercept = 0.5) + 
  geom_vline(xintercept = 0)
g

Q4: When power functions look linear

Consider the three graphs that the following code produces. Note: I dont need to see the graphs in the version you turn in. Please put echo=FALSE on line 60 once you finish looking at the graphs.

Comment carefully on the differences you see between the three versions. Then explain why a function of the form \(y = x^p\) looks linear on a log-log plot. Hint: let \(w = \log_{10}(y)\) and let \(t = \log_{10}(x)\), then show that there is a linear relationship between \(t\) and \(w\).

Solution:

In the first version, which is the original dot plot of function \(y = x^{-2}\), the x-axis ranges from 1 to 1000, and y-axis ranges from 0 to 1.

In the second version, we manually change the x-axis and y-axis into \(log_{10}(x)\) and \(log_{10}(y)\), the plot shows the fucntion \(y = -2x\). In this plot, the X range is also from 1 to 1000, in other words, \(log_{10}(x)\) ranges from 1 to 3, and \(log_{10}(y)\) ranges from -6 to 0.

In the third version, we can see although it looks like the same as the second plot, however, this plot does not show the funtion \(y=-2x\), instead it shows \(y = x^{-2}\). The reason it looks similar to the second one is that both the axises are all logarithmic through the code log=xy, it exists dramatic difference in the x-axis and y-axis.

Proof:

Let \(w= log_{10}(y)\), \(t=log_{10}(x)\).

We can get \[y = x^{p} = (10^{t})^{p} = 10^{tp} = 10^{w}\] Thus, \(w = tp\), which is a linear relationship between \(w\) and \(t\).

Q5: Create a letter

As on the Day 1 activity, create a color image showing the first letter of your name by building appropriate matrices in R. Give it a white background (initialize the matrices with 1s instead of 0s). Add it to the Google Doc, and also include it here.

Solution:

library('magick')
## Linking to ImageMagick 6.9.12.3
## Enabled features: cairo, fontconfig, freetype, heic, lcms, pango, raw, rsvg, webp
## Disabled features: fftw, ghostscript, x11
myRed <- matrix(1,500,500) # a 500x500 grid of zeros
myRed[0:500,0:500] <- 1 # change some entries into ones

myGreen <- matrix(1,500,500)
myBlue <- matrix(1,500,500)
shiftleft <- 100
shiftDown <- 100
for (x in 0 : 100) {
  for (t in 0 : 50) {
    t <- t - shiftleft
    myGreen[x+shiftDown, 400+x+t] <- 0
    myRed[x+shiftDown, 400-x+t] <- 0
    myBlue[100+x+shiftDown, 300+x+t] <- 0
    myBlue[195+x+shiftDown, 395+x+t] <- 0
    myRed[395-x+shiftDown, 395+x+t] <- 0
    myGreen[395-x+shiftDown, 395-x+t] <- 0
  }

}
data <- array(c(myRed,myGreen,myBlue),dim = c(500,500,3))

im <- image_read(data) 
print(im) # this displays the image in RStudio and knitted documents
## # A tibble: 1  7
##   format width height colorspace matte filesize density
##   <chr>  <int>  <int> <chr>      <lgl>    <int> <chr>  
## 1 PNG      500    500 sRGB       FALSE        0 72x72

image_write(im,"mycolors.png")

Q6: High contrast image

The image Department.png is a cropped version of a photo by Stefani Reynolds in a January 2023 article about the upcoming US debt ceiling crisis in the New York Times. It shows part of the Treasury Department building in Washington. It is a color image, but it looks pretty gray because for most pixels, the values in the R, G, and B channels are all close together. Save the image in the same folder as your main RMD file and then uncomment these lines to see it:

library("magick")
a = image_read("Department.png")
A = as.integer(a[[1]])/256
redA = A[,,1]
greenA = A[,,2]
blueA = A[,,3]
print(a) # this displays the image in RStudio and knitted documents
## # A tibble: 1  7
##   format width height colorspace matte filesize density
##   <chr>  <int>  <int> <chr>      <lgl>    <int> <chr>  
## 1 PNG      370    382 sRGB       FALSE   247388 57x57

We will make a high-contrast version of this image using a new code trick: updating a matrix or vector using conditional tests.

Here is a first example where we create a vector and then ask which entries are less than 5:

v <- 1:8
print(v)
## [1] 1 2 3 4 5 6 7 8
print(v < 5)
## [1]  TRUE  TRUE  TRUE  TRUE FALSE FALSE FALSE FALSE

The useful trick is that you can update the entries for which the condition is true:

v[v<5] <- -1
print(v)
## [1] -1 -1 -1 -1  5  6  7  8

The same trick works for matrices and high-dimensional arrays:

a <- matrix(rnorm(12),3,4) # create a 3x4 matrix with normally distributed entries
a[a<0] <- 0 # set all negative elements to be zero
print(a) # we should see about half zeros, half positive numbers
##                   [,1]               [,2]               [,3]               [,4]
## [1,] 1.981957690300111 0.0000000000000000 0.2775521379449278 0.0000000000000000
## [2,] 0.000000000000000 1.4072631564513449 0.6131437760934116 1.5708595736817097
## [3,] 0.000000000000000 0.3720784720167044 0.0000000000000000 0.2771285249353808

The three matrices redA, greenA, and blueA contain numbers between 0 and 1. Pick a cutoff between 0 and 1 (0.5 is a good choice but you can experiment) and then set all entries to 1 if theyre greater than the cutoff, or 0 otherwise. Then display the altered image, the high contrast version. It should be mostly black-and-white but there will be some colored pixels - explain why.

Solution:

library("magick")
A[redA < 0.4] <- 0
A[blueA<0.4] <- 0
A[greenA<0.4] <- 0
hc <- image_read(A)
print(hc)
## # A tibble: 1  7
##   format width height colorspace matte filesize density
##   <chr>  <int>  <int> <chr>      <lgl>    <int> <chr>  
## 1 PNG      370    382 sRGB       FALSE        0 72x72

In the image, we can find most of the pixels are black or white, but there still exist some pixels with colors. When we change the numbers in the three matrices, the number will be 0 or 1. So when we got (0, 0, 0), the color will be black and when we got (1, 1, 1), the color will be white. However, when there just exist one 1 or two 1s, for example (1, 1, 0) or (1, 0, 0), the pixel will have other colors, yellow or red.
